{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499415"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:59:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:59:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1495"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1495"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.08,0.12,0.65,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1495"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106272"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1495"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1495"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88740"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"456"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13156"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13758"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13954"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39137"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106272"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a three-month history of intermittent left upper quadrant pain. She has a medical history of hypertension and hypothyroidism, for which she takes perindopril and thyroxine. She does not smoke and drinks two glasses of wine per week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 136/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft with mild tenderness and fullness in the left upper quadrant. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable. A CT scan of her abdomen reveals a well-circumscribed lesion with rim calcification (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pancreatic pseudocyst","Adrenal cyst","Gastrointestinal stromal tumour","Splenic hydatid cyst","Liver abscess"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT shows a large, well-circumscribed lesion in the spleen with a characteristic calcified rim. This appearance is highly suggestive of a \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenic hydatid cyst\u003C/strong\u003E. Hydatid disease is caused by the tapeworm \u003Cem\u003EEchinococcus granulosus\u003C/em\u003E, where dogs are the definitive host and sheep are intermediate hosts. Humans become infected through accidental ingestion of eggs from infected dog faeces. The condition is more common in rural Australia, especially in those who have occupational exposure to sheep, making collection of a social and occupational history important in these cases. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreatic pseudocyst\u003C/strong\u003E typically appears as a well-defined, fluid-filled lesion adjacent to the pancreas. It usually lacks calcification and is generally associated with a history of pancreatitis, which is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eadrenal cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare lesion that appears as a well-defined, low-density lesion arising from the adrenal gland. While often detected incidentally on imaging, it typically does not show rim calcification and would be in a different anatomical location.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Egastrointestinal stromal tumour\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents as a solid, enhancing mass arising from the wall of the stomach or small intestine. While it may have areas of necrosis or cystic degeneration, it rarely shows calcification and would not be within the spleen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver abscess\u003C/strong\u003E typically appears as a low-density lesion with an irregular, enhancing rim. It may have internal septations or air bubbles but does not usually show calcification. Additionally, this lesion is clearly within the spleen, not the liver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile hydatid cysts most commonly occur in the liver (50-70% of cases), splenic involvement occurs in 2-3% of cases. Many hydatid cysts remain asymptomatic and are discovered incidentally on imaging. When symptoms do occur, they are usually due to mass effect on surrounding structures or complications such as rupture or secondary infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hydatid cysts are characterised by a rim of calcification on imaging and are often asymptomatic.","Splenic hydatid cysts are less common than hepatic hydatid cysts, which are the most frequent presentation.","Hydatid disease is caused by ingestion of Echinococcus granulosus eggs from infected dog faeces, particularly in sheep-farming regions."],"references":["Higuita NIA, Brunetti E, McCloskey C. Cystic Echinococcosis. J Clin Microbiol. 2016; 54:518-23. Available at: https://journals.asm.org/doi/10.1128/jcm.02420-15"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88740"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1495"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15326"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15326"},"attributes":{"mime